{u'list_9048040_choice': None, u'list_6462402_choice_8148701': None, u'fileupload_7219011': None, u'textarea_7603814': None, u'list_9115461_other': None, u'list_10881559_choice': u'Capture the spirit of the source material', u'textfield_10176495': None, u'list_6462402_other': None, u'list_9117425_choice': u'Important. The Panda needs to know what to expect.', u'dropdown_7603830': u'Economics', u'email_8765490': None, u'textarea_10173448': u'Ian.Driscoll@amcham-shanghai.org Nearly one-third of U.S. companies (29 percent) reported that China is their number one global investment priority \x13 a record high. Almost all companies surveyed \x13 96 percent \x13 reported they had maintained or increased investment levels in China operations for 2014, with the same number forecasting a similar investment intent for 2015.
 
More companies are at the low to moderate end of planned investment increases for 2015, with 41 percent indicating increases in the 1 to 15 percent range, and 21 percent planning increases of 16 to 50 percent. These numbers reflect a shift to the lower end of investment levels, with a steady decline over the past five years in the number of companies planning high investment increases.
 
For the small number of companies planning to decrease their investment in 2015 (4.4 percent), the reasons given are rising costs and expectations of slower growth in China.
 
\x1cIn China for China\x1d Strategy
 
For U.S. businesses the shift towards an \x1cin China, for China\x1d strategy strengthened, indicating a confidence in future market opportunities. A record 67 percent reported that their company\x19s number one priority is to produce or source goods or services in China for the China market. Conversely, a strategy and business line focused on manufacturing and production in China for the U.S. and other markets continued to decline, a reflection of both the changing nature of U.S. business operations in China and its high-cost environment.
 
Optimism High But Signs of a Shift
